I. Introduction and Motivation¶

The medical/healthcare industry is moving rapidly towards analytics. People make appointments with doctors, follow all the instructions, receive messages reminding them of their appointments, and yet they still end up missing their appointments. According to sources, it costs US health care system $150 billion a year when patients miss the appointments. What if it was possible to predict no-shows? If we are able to predict the show ups, we can optimize the usage of the resources and schedule maximum appointments in a day.

The domain of the problem is a pure binary classification task (supervised learning). To make it a little more interesting, we want to see how unsupervised learning can be implemented within a supervised learning task.

We took data from Kaggle : https://www.kaggle.com/joniarroba/noshowappointments/home. This data is from hospitals in a region from Brazil for three months in 2016.

The data included patients with negative age, so we removed such rows. In addition, we removed the time component from scheduled day because it interfered with our calculations for some of the features we extracted. Last, we removed rows where the appointment is less than the scheduled day as you can't schedule an appointment for a prior day.

V. Functions¶

Below are some functions that we have reused throughout the project.

The encoding method takes a dataframe and does label encoding or one-hot encoding depending upon the number of unique columns in the column in the data frame and returns the new data frame.

The train class has two method of cluster and classify. We use to either do clustering on the data set that is passed or do classification depending on which function is called. We can pass different models to these functions and the function will take of it accordingly. The result of the clustering technique will be used as a feature.

In [8]:
def encoding(df):
    column_types = df.dtypes
    objectType_cols = list(column_types[column_types=='object'].index)
    for cols in objectType_cols:
        if(len(df[cols].unique())>2):
            label_encode = pd.get_dummies(df[cols])
            df.drop(cols,axis=1, inplace=True)
            df = pd.merge(df,label_encode,left_index=True, right_index=True)
        elif(len(df[cols].unique())==2):
            df[cols].replace(df[cols].unique(),[0,1],inplace=True)
    return df
In [9]:
class train(object):
    def __init__(self, train, test):
        train_data = train.copy()
        test_data = test.copy()
        
        n,m = train.shape
    
        self.X_train, self.y_train = train_data.iloc[:,:m-1], train_data.iloc[:,m-1]
        self.X_test, self.y_test = test_data.iloc[:, :m-1], test_data.iloc[:, m-1]
    
    def classify(self, model=LogisticRegression(random_state=42)): #default classification model is Logistic Regression
        model.fit(self.X_train, self.y_train)
        if(isinstance(model,RandomForestClassifier)):
            feature_importances = pd.DataFrame(model.feature_importances_,index = self.X_train.columns,columns=['importance']).sort_values('importance',ascending=False)
            print(feature_importances.head(5))

        y_pred = model.predict_proba(self.X_test)[:,1]
        return(self.y_test, y_pred)
        
    def cluster(self, model=KMeans(n_clusters=2, random_state=42), output='add'): #default clustering model is Kmeans
        model.fit(self.X_train)
        y_labels_train = model.labels_
        y_labels_test = model.predict(self.X_test)
        if output == 'add':
            self.X_train['km_clust'] = y_labels_train
            self.X_test['km_clust'] = y_labels_test
        else:
            raise ValueError('output should be add')
        
        return self

Methodology of our analysis¶

Step 1: One Hot Encoding Step 2: Train/Test Split Step 3: Hyper Parameter Tuning Step 4: Pass Models (Logistic Regression, Naive Bayes, and Random Forest) with the optimal parameters from Step 3 to a Cross Validation Class to perform model fitting and prediction Step 5: Repeat Process: a. After fixing class imbalance b. After fixing class imbalance and performing feature engineering and re-tuning the models

2. Hyperparameter Tuning¶

a. Hyperparameter Tuning for Logistic Regression¶

In [12]:
logistic = LogisticRegression()
C = [1e-2,1e-1,1,10,100]

hyperparameters = dict(C=C)
clf = GridSearchCV(logistic, hyperparameters, cv=5, verbose=0, scoring='roc_auc')

n,m = kaggle.shape
X, Y = kaggle.iloc[:,:m-1], kaggle.iloc[:,m-1]
best_model = clf.fit(X, Y)

print('Best Parameters',clf.best_params_)
print('Best C:', best_model.best_estimator_.get_params()['C'])
best_cLR = best_model.best_estimator_.get_params()['C']

Best Parameters {'C': 0.01}
Best C: 0.01

In all of the models, we only tuned one parameter because it would take an unnecessarily long time (approximately 30-40 minutes) to tune many paramaters for each model. For Logistic Regression, we tuned the parameter C. The paramater C is the inverse of regularization strength. Similar to Support Vector Machines, the smaller the value, the stronger the regularization strength. In this case, the best C had a value of 0.01.

We included Logistic Regression because we wanted to test our data using a basic parametric model. However, because logistic regression tends to overfit with more features, we tuned the paramater C in hopes of finding a balance. In our case, the one-hot encoding increased the number of features dramatically.

b. Hyperparameter Tuning for Naive Bayes¶

In [13]:
bNB = BernoulliNB()
alphas = np.array([0.001,0.01,0.1,1,10,100])

hyperparameters = dict(alpha=alphas)
clf = GridSearchCV(bNB, hyperparameters, cv=5, verbose=0, scoring='roc_auc')

n,m = kaggle.shape
X, Y = kaggle.iloc[:,:m-1], kaggle.iloc[:,m-1]
best_model = clf.fit(X, Y)

print('Best Parameters',clf.best_params_)
print('Best Alpha:', best_model.best_estimator_.get_params()['alpha'])
best_alpha = best_model.best_estimator_.get_params()['alpha']

Best Parameters {'alpha': 1.0}
Best Alpha: 1.0

We included Naive Bayes because Naive Bayes does not tend to overfit even if the number of features increases. Again, in our case, the number of features increased because of the one-hot encoding. Therefore, Naive Bayes seemed like a suitable classifier.

We modified the alpha parameter which is an Additive (Laplace/Lidstone) smoothing parameter. In this case, the best alpha was 1 which is the same as the default alpha value.

Finally, we included Random Forest because it is a powerful classifier that can allow us to ascertain which features are the most important, and it is also has much less variability that a simple Decision Tree model.

For the Random Forest model, we tuned the depth of the tree, and the best depth was 18.

2. Default Modelling¶

a. Logistic Regression Default ROC¶

Analysis of our basic modeling¶

From our previous EDA, and the relatively high accuracy scores for each model, we immediately believed there was some sort of issue with our default data. The AUC scores from the ROC curves, which is the main metric we use to determine our best model later, seemed relatively similar as well.

After some researching, we determined that class imbalance was our issue. We also learned that ROC curves and AUC scores are insensitive to class imbalace. In the next step, we observed that insensitivity. The curves don't change even after resolving class imbalance. Furthermore, we also learned that in cases with class imbalance, accuracy scores are relatively high. Again, in the next step, after fixing class imbalance, those accuracy scores decrease.

Finally, we decided to bring in another metric such as F1_score (balance between precision and recall) to test whether class imbalance was really the issue. For each model above, the F1_score is almost close to zero.

To fix class imbalance, we down-sampled the majority class. Another approach that could have been taken is to upsample the minority class. I assume upsampling is a better approach because you don't end up losing any data points.

As mentioned above, even after resolving class imbalance, none of the ROC Curves for any of the models changed. However, the accuracy scores for the seperate models decreased, while the F1-score increased for each model. This supported our intuition that class imbalance was an issue that needed to be resolved.

4. Adding features¶

Over here, we decided to add three additional features. The first feature we decided to add was the days between the appointment day and the scheduled day. We believed this was important because generally people won't miss an appointment if you have scheduled it for an immediate date. If there is an appointment that is booked a month in prior you might not be very serious about the appointment.

In addition, from the age feature, we created bins for the different age groups. We extracted bins for baby, child, teenager, young adults, adult, and elder categories.

The next feature we added was whether the appointment was a followup or not. We believed this was important under the assumption that people generally tend to miss their appointments if its a follow up appointment.

    km = KMeans(n_clusters=k)
    #drop the last column which is the "y"
    km = km.fit(kaggle_addFeatures.iloc[:,:m-1])
    Sum_of_squared_distances.append(km.inertia_)
    
plt.plot(K, Sum_of_squared_distances, 'bx-')
plt.xlabel('k')
plt.ylabel('Sum_of_squared_distances')
plt.title('Elbow Method For Optimal k')
plt.show()

#Split the age in different categories. We take -1 so that zero is inclusive

#Find if appointment is a followup
X_test_addFeatures =X_test_addFeatures.sort_values(by=['PatientId', 'AppointmentDay'], ascending=[True,True]).reset_index()
X_test_addFeatures['isFollowUp'] = 0
for index, row in X_test_addFeatures.iterrows():
    if(index!=len(X_test_addFeatures)-1):
        if(row['PatientId']==X_test_addFeatures.iloc[index+1]['PatientId']):
            if(int(str(X_test_addFeatures.iloc[index+1]['AppointmentDay']-row['AppointmentDay']).strip().split()[0])<=30):
                X_test_addFeatures.set_value(index,'isFollowUp',1)

V. Conclusion¶

After resolving class imbalance, tuning the different parameters for Logistic Regression, Naive Bayes, and Random Forest, and adding four additional features, Random Forest was our best model. The Random Forest model had an AUC score of 0.797. The best threshold for this model was 0.52.

Using this threshold, we were able to identiy the patients that were misclassified and classified by our model. After realizing that there is no systematic difference between the patients that were misclassified and classified, we realized that we needed more information to discern such a difference.

Therefore, our assessment should further incentivize hospitals to provide more information in hopes that models like ours can help more precisely determine whether a patient will miss their appointment or not. The extra information could include reasons why a patient is visiting the hospital, some cost parameter, and data that spans more than just three months. Ultimately, our assessment can help hospitals target patients that are more likely to skip there appointments, and reach out to them in advance to lower the rate of missed appointments.
